      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA implementations (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) operate under documented software quality management systems. Version control, regression testing, and release validation procedures are in place. Achieved level equals required level for this model risk category."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from published literature solved with known analytical solutions; residuals below solver tolerance thresholds.",
      "rationale": "Each FEA code was verified against standard benchmark problems including beam bending and contact patch tests. Residual norms confirmed below 1e-6. Independent ensemble agreement provides additional cross-verification evidence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates less than 2% change in peak von Mises stress between successive refinements.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was performed with three refinement levels. Peak von Mises stress at the screw-rod junction changed by less than 1.8% between the medium and fine meshes. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, balancing accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver convergence confirmed; energy balance error below 0.5%.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterations converged within 15 increments for all load cases. Energy balance errors were below 0.3% across all 11 construct simulations. Contact stabilization parameters were verified to have negligible influence on reported quantities of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup reviewed by independent analyst; boundary condition application documented and traceable.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst reviewed all boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and load application procedures against the documented simulation protocol. No discrepancies were identified. All inputs are traceable to the experimental test configuration per ASTM F1717."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Physics assumptions documented and justified; linear elastic material model appropriate for sub-yield loading regime.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic isotropic material models are appropriate for the titanium alloy components under ASTM F1717 sub-yield loading. Frictional contact with a coefficient of 0.2 was applied at all interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity was included to capture large-displacement effects in the flexible rod. Model form assumptions are consistent with prior FDA-published pedicle screw analyses."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports; geometric dimensions measured from physical specimens.",
      "rationale": "Young's modulus and Poisson's ratio for Ti-6Al-4V ELI were taken from certified material test reports supplied by DePuy Synthes. Component geometry was digitized via micro-CT at 20 µm resolution. Dimensional uncertainty was propagated through a sensitivity analysis confirming less than 4% influence on predicted construct stiffness."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 experimental specimens from production lot; sample variability characterized.",
      "rationale": "N=11 production-lot constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. Coefficient of variation in construct stiffness was 6.2%, within acceptable bounds. Sample lot traceability was confirmed via device history records."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple loading conditions tested to characterize model performance across the intended use envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single compression-bending load condition per ASTM F1717. While this condition is clinically relevant, only one test configuration was evaluated, limiting characterization of model performance across the broader loading envelope. This factor is below the required level and represents a known gap in the validation evidence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and material inputs demonstrably equivalent to experimental test configuration.",
      "rationale": "Fixture geometry, load application points, and constraint conditions in the FEA models were mapped directly to the physical test fixture drawings. Material certificates confirmed composition and heat treatment equivalence between modeled and tested material batches."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted construct stiffness within ±15% of experimental mean; prediction interval overlaps experimental distribution.",
      "rationale": "Predicted construct stiffness from all three FEA implementations fell within ±10% of the experimental mean (N=11). The ensemble prediction interval fully overlapped the experimental 95% confidence interval. Bland-Altman analysis confirmed no systematic bias."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantities of interest (construct stiffness, peak stress) are directly linked to the clinical and regulatory question of interest.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and peak von Mises stress at the screw-rod junction are the primary quantities of interest, directly corresponding to the ASTM F1717 acceptance criteria and the biomechanical performance endpoints relevant to spinal fusion support. These quantities are established in the regulatory submission context."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity geometry, loading, and material conditions are representative of the intended use scenario.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 test protocol replicates the in vivo loading environment for posterior spinal fixation constructs. The validated model geometry (7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screw) and loading conditions are directly representative of the device configuration and use scenario for which the FEA model is intended to provide evidence."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed the required level for model risk level 3. The single deficiency in Test conditions (achieved level 2 vs. required level 3) is acknowledged; the assessment team determined that the single ASTM F1717 compression-bending condition is the primary clinically relevant scenario and that the overall body of evidence is sufficient to support the regulatory submission decision. The FEA model ensemble agreement across three independent implementations provides additional confidence. Acceptance is conditional on restricting model use to the compression-bending loading regime evaluated in this validation activity.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
